  "prompt": "What are some functions of human cell membranes?",
  "response": "Human cell membranes, primarily composed of a phospholipid bilayer with embedded proteins, serve several crucial functions, including:\n\n1. **Barrier Function**: The cell membrane acts as a selective barrier, controlling the movement of substances in and out of the cell. It maintains the internal environment of the cell, ensuring homeostasis.\n\n2. **Transport**: The membrane contains various transport proteins that facilitate the movement of ions, nutrients, and waste products. This includes passive transport (e.g., diffusion, osmosis) and active transport mechanisms.\n\n3. **Cell Communication**: Membrane proteins, particularly receptors, play a vital role in cell signaling. They can receive signals from hormones and other molecules, allowing the cell to respond to changes in its environment.\n\n4. **Cell Adhesion**: Cell membranes have molecules that enable cells to adhere to each other and to the extracellular matrix. This is important for tissue formation and maintenance.\n\n5. **Recognition**: Glycoproteins and glycolipids on the cell surface function as identification markers, allowing cells to recognize each other. This is crucial for immune response and tissue compatibility.\n\n6. **Structural Support**: The membrane provides structural integrity to the cell. It helps maintain the shape of the cell and protects against mechanical stress.\n\n7. **Endocytosis and Exocytosis**: The cell membrane is involved in the processes of endocytosis (uptake of materials into the cell) and exocytosis (release of materials from the cell), which are essential for nutrient uptake and waste removal.\n\n8. **Energy Production**: In certain cells, the membrane is involved in energy production processes, such as in mitochondria, where the inner membrane plays a key role in the electron transport chain and ATP synthesis.\n\n9. **Signal Transduction**: The membrane is involved in converting external signals into internal responses through pathways that involve second messengers, ultimately leading to cellular responses.\n\nThese functions are essential for the overall functioning and survival of human cells and play a vital role in maintaining the health of the entire organism.",
